title: Dillner 20-32-C Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (37.59g thrust @3V)

description.text:
This micro drone propeller was inspired and designed after the Dillner 20-32-C airfoil. It was tested on the Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (results below).

It was printed slowly, with a 0.2 nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. I deburred and cleaned the print with a Precision Knife

After this, I got to finishing the part using a 500 grit sandpaper.

Here are the measurements for a few voltage presets (you can also check these out in the images):

  • 1.5V => 11.21 grams
  • 2V => 16.57 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.43 grams
  • 3V => 37.59 grams

The files you'll download consist of all the pictures taken during the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. Should you like to use the propeller, make sure you have a 8520 coreless motor.

You should use the SLDPRT extension files, should you wish to make your own changes to the propeller.

P.S. The airfoil plotted with the matplotlib library in python.

title: Whippersnapper Front and Rear Contact Bumpers

description.text:
The basic bumper consists of four parts. They must be assembled and you will need some momentary contact switches, some small hardware, and a couple of small springs. The pictures should give you the information needed for basic assembly.

The fifth stl file, drill guide, is used to locate the two 1/8" (3mm) holes in the rear of the robot top plate to mount the bumper assembly. The actual bumper is 8" wide and only 1/16" inch thick. This makes it flexible enough that only one side can actuate if the contact is only on a single side. That was you have three potential conditions from each bumper; left contact, right contact, full contact. And can program the robot to deal with those three conditions.

title: The Open Source Outboard
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Description:

The Open Source Outboard is a 3d printable outboard motor for rc watercraft. It is an original design that was developed as part of a larger effort of making an radio controlled fishing boat, a lofty goal. If you are going to shoot into the sky, at least aim for a star. That’s what mama always said.

View the Github Page for more information!

Disclaimer:

This is an adult toy and it should be used with caution. It has a blade that can spin very fast, held together with plastic threads extruded by your printer. I don’t trust my printer to make a shelf bracket that would hang above my head. So I do not EVER run this out of the water. One has not jettisoned yet, but it is a demonstrated possibility. PLEASE BE SAFE!

Videos

Open Source Outboard - Version 1 - Testing
[Single Motor Steering System - Version ALPHA - Build Log]
Open Source Outboard - Version 1 - Design Review
Open Source Outboard - Version 1 - Build Log
(https://youtu.be/_XBBsyASD9s)
Dual Motor Steering System - Version ALPHA - Build Log

Bill of Materials

I'm linking to Amazon because it is fast and convenient. There are better prices to be found. I'm also linking to Accugroup because I like their selection and the hardware has been great quality. I live in the states and they are in the uk, but its worth the wait in my opinion. I only use stainless/torx type because dealing with a stripped screw in plastic is frustrating to put it politely.

Open Source Outboard

  • Required RC Electronics: the type is optional, these are my choices.
    • Transmitter/Receiver
    • ESC (usually bought with motor)
    • 3s Lipo Battery or 2s Lipo Battery
  • Sensorless Brushless Motor
    • Supported Sizes
      • 2845, 3650 (no water cooler support)
  • 4mm stainless steel rod
  • Stainless Steel Fasteners
    • (4) M3x6mm
    • (2) M3x8mm
    • (2) M3x10mm
    • (1) M3x14mm
    • (4) M3 Nuts
    • (1) M3 Nylon Locking Nut
    • (3) 4mm ID Flanged Bearings
    • (1) 3.17mm to 4mm Shaft Coupler Much less expensive internationally
  • (1) Water Pump

Single Motor Steering System

  • Mini Servo
  • (2) 3mm ID flanged bearings
  • Stainless Steel Fasteners
    • (3) M3x8mm
    • (1) M3x10mm
    • (1) M3x20mm
    • (1) M3x30mm
    • (3) M3x50mm
    • (5) M3 Nylon Locking Nut
    • (3) M3 Nuts

Dual Motor Steering System

  • Mini Servo
  • (7) 3mm ID flanged bearings
  • Stainless Steel Fasteners
    • (6) M3x8mm
    • (8) M3x10mm
    • (2) M3x20mm
    • (2) M3x25mm
    • (6) M3x50mm
    • (22) M3 Nylon Locking Nut
    • (2) M3 Nuts
Print Settings

Needs to be printed with a filament that has little shrinkage. I use PET-G, ABS is an option. PLA may not work, I haven't tried it however. These settings are required, because the design has dimensions that are multiples of that line width. This means all the parts can be printed at the same time. It also means, that if you find your hardware does not fit well (screws should slide through with little resistance, nuts should drop in nut traps but hold when being threaded) you can adjust the scale of the entire assembly. All the parts will fit together still and the hardware hole should change. This could affect the way the slicer plans the print, so check the layers for gaps before printing. Gaps in the walls is bad.

  • .4mm nozzle
  • .4mm line width
  • .4mm wall thickness
  • 100% infill
  • No supports
  • .2mm layer height or better
More Info

I have only tested it at .2mm layer height. Up to the adventurous to try it at a higher resolution.

The walls are built around a .4mm line width, so the walls range from 0.8mm (2 lines thick) to 1.8mm thick. If the wall thickness is set larger Cura would leave an empty cavity in the walls.

Clean up and preparation

Clean off any loose filament strands. Ream out axle hole in bottom of midsection - it has 2 layers at the ceiling to improve the bridging. Nothing should require much fiddling to get to fit.

Time

I learned Fusion 360, then started building. I made a couple other versions before this, and added the things up that I learned and this is what I got.

title: Bigger MP Select Mini Z Axis Spacer - No Disassembly - Fusion 360

description.text:
This is a Z Axis spacer for the MP Select Mini.

Every other Z Axis spacer I've tried for my printer didn't quite fit. The spacer wouldn't fit the front-to-back depth of the gantry, causing the part not to be flat, causing the z spacing to be different than advertised.

Xilvar's spacer looked really good, but I couldn't quite get the results I wanted with that openSCAD file. So, I copied the basic shape in a Fusion 360 design. Files with a pretty good range of extra z space are included, but you can customize in Fusion 360 if you like. In Fusion 360, just go to "Modify->Change Parameters" and change the zExtraSpace parameter to the amount of extra space you need on the z axis.

There is a little tiny B for Bottom on one of the ends. This shows you which side goes down when inserting the spacer.

description.text:
Anet A6 power switch

I was not able to find an existing thing to install a power switch at the back of the printer for the original power supply so i created this one.

Installation

The top hole of the switch was designed to align with the hole at the power switch thats why you need 40mm screws. Because of the small space its a bit hard to fit the screw at the inner side. i used a short (~9cm) screwdriver for this. Since i am not an electronics expert i was not aware that the switch comes without a fuse so keep that in mind. Because the power supply is specified as 12V 20A it could provide 240W at max. That means at 230V there is at max 1A. So i think my spare fuses marked 1.6A 250V should be sufficient.

used switch:
https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B01ID44I4S/

used screws:

  • 2 x M4, 40mm (switch)
  • 2 x M3, 30mm (to replace existing but shorter screws)
    30mm fits but feels a bit short, 35mm should be perfect.
  • 1 x M3 (inner side, existing screw can be reused)

I guess, there are other cases too, where the traditional hinges could be changed to flex material.

I have added the file "hinge_multi.stl", that prints 8 full sized hinges. Cut the hinges after printing with a scissors. They are printed together to prevent moving under the nozzle while printing.

I stake this is the only fidget cube, that could be printed with wood filament, isn't it?
I have added two files called integrated_support. The hole at the top is closed on both ends (only 1 mm) for easier printing, Open the hole with a small knife after printing.

description.text:
Iwahiro's Apparently Impossible Cube is an example of a coordinate motion puzzle - all the pieces have to be moved into place at the same time.
You can find the original at http://puzzlewillbeplayed.com/444/IwahiroAIC/1/

Print of 2 of each piece at a fine resolution. I used a layer height of 0.2 mm from a 0.3 mm nozzle.
The pieces have been designed with a small bevel on the edges and a slight offset to give a snug fit (but this may vary on your printer).
You can watch a video of the puzzle in action (including the solution, so don't watch it if you want to try and solve it yourself) at http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1J8fA3t3Y78

comments.text: mine are to tite to fit together will scalinig it up work or is ther one with bigger tolorances

Yes, scaling up the size will also increase the size of the gap between the pieces.
However, the usual cause of the parts being too tight to fit together is 'over-extrusion' of plastic. If your printer is over-extruding, the only place the excess can go is outwards and this can easily fill the 0.1 mm gap between parts.
Try lowering the extrusion multiplier in your slicer, perhaps to 95% or even 90% and have another try.
Adjacent lines of filament should only just touch each other in a solid filled layer. It is a good idea to decrease the extrusion multiplier until you start to see gaps between the lines and then increase it just a little bit to make them touch again.

I printed this with thick wall (4+) to give it strenght. Just watch the gears as they may need a different setting to keep holes from appearing in the sliccer.
Have had recent issues with Cura 2.5, but ran it through 3D Builder and saved it as a 3mf file type and it slices fine.(5/18/17)

Dry run

Last edited 5/20/17
After cleaning up the print and using a file to detail the gears, hot glue the M5 hex head bolt into the Planetary Carrier Top, assemble the gear box leaving the housing loose, then use three M5 nuts tightened on the output shaft, use a wrench turn the output shaft back and forth till it breaks free and will rotate. Switch to a drill and use a low setting and if it has it, the clutch turned down. Using the drill, as the gears wear-in it will get easier to turn, when this happends increase the speed and run it forward and backward. Once you are satified that it is running fine, then tighten the housing up a little at a time, repeating the drill proceedure. After you are done disassemble the gear box and reassemble it using tread tight on the six internal screws (3-M3 w/ nuts and 3-M2 w/ nuts) holding the Planetary Carrier (Top and Bottom) together. Add White Lithium Grease to the gears and inside the housing. Finish assembley by mounting it to a Nema 17. Use the nema to turn the Sun Gear and you will see some of the Lithium Grease coming out the top, this is normal.
Vitamins list: 3- M3x18mm w/ nuts( mounts Top Planetary Carrier through Planetary Gears to Lower Planetary Carrier) , 3-M2x18mm w/nuts, 4-M3x30mm(mounts gear box to Nema 17 through standard metal motor mount),( 1-M3x30mm w/nuts , 3-M3x45mm w/nuts (mounts MK8 extruder to gear box)), and 1-M5x30 w/3nuts and 1 washer.

Prepareing to make a video of assembley.
I used multiple tools to design this, http://geargenerator.com, Freecad and Sketchup8.

title: Ride height gauge for 1/10-scale RC Buggy

description.text:
Most 1/10-scale RC buggies need to be set to a ride height of 23mm, 24mm, or 25mm. Or some combination thereof: Losi 22's are often set to 23/24 front/rear.  
This not-quite-cubical block has three lengths: 23mm, 24mm, and 25mm. Just drop the buggy onto a smooth surface, then adjust the ride height so that this block just slides under the chassis when the desired number is right-side up. In other words, if you look at the block from the side and the '24' is right-side-up on the side of the block, then that side of the block is 24mm high.

improvement of older work You can read the background of this topic on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2312813, which has the same usage as this small case.
The background for this Thing however is to get rid of all parts you cannot print in 3d and as one part!
It took some prints to get the right distance to let the hinge move, but it works fine now.

Clean up code First, I reduced many unnecessary and redundant code lines and used for every part that came at least twice, the “modeule()” function of openSCAD, which I should use from the beginning for the screw clamp case. The right functionality For the hinge it’s very important that the nuckle and the pin are mirrored on the other side! Otherwise the two parts will get loose. To get a good moving hinge I needed a distance of 0.2 mm.
I think it depends on your accuracy of your printer. The right wall thickness I’m using a 0.4 mm nozzle on my Prusa i3. The printed model at the images has a wall thickness of 1.2 mm which means it gets TWO walls with a distance of 0.4 mm. This causes a brittle wall which you can split in two with you finger nails or even the hinge breaks out - like in the last image (the back of the closed case).
To avoid this, you need to print a two-layered wall with a wall thickness of 0.8 mm and a layer thickness of 0.4mm, or a 1.6 mm thick wall with four layers an layer thickness of 0.8 mm in your printer setting
Good print settings If your printer is well configured, you don't need anything else as this Thing.

Green or red ABS filament is used, so no painting is needed. Transparent ABS is used for the lamp lens.

title: X Axis motor mount for Anet A8 or Prusa i3

description.text:
This is a ground-up redesign of "thing" 1428253 using Fusion 360. I used a slight teardrop shape at the top (when printing) of the horizontal holes to avoid sagging on the bridging at the top of the holes. I also used 1mm fillets at all of the corners, so the printer would not have to slowdown or overrun tight corners. These changes allowed the tolerance to be a lot tighter than the original design. The holes are 8.18mm (originally 8.6), although I did have to use some light bearing oil to slide the rods in. Linear bearing holes are slightly tighter too (15.08 vs. 15.2). There are other cosmetic and functional changes.

After you print, you probably want to sand the bottom (that will be the top when flipped). I used 600 sandpaper. This is in case there was any curling/warping off the bed during printing. You want those huge nuts for the z-axis screws to be as level as possible.

All of the screws and nuts are 3mm in my design. I used a left over 45mm screw from my printer for the pulley/thumbscrew. I also used 3mm locknuts, although plain nuts should work too.

Printing

  • Depending on your printer, use either the standard Left/Right files which have 45mm spacing between rod axes, or the 44mm/46mm variants of those files.
  • Do not use supports
  • Enable Avoid crossing perimeters or equivalent so you don't have any garbage to clean up where the rods or linear bearing go.
  • The test_fit.stl file can be used to check how tight the fit is with your printer and slicer settings. The hole in this file is the normal (8.18mm) size.

Assembly

After inserting the horizontal rods, rotate both of them in place (simultaneously) to relieve any stress on your Z-axis rods. Then tighten the two outer screws on the "tensioner" just enough that it begins to separate. This ensures that the horizontal rods are providing the belt tension (and not your Z-axis).

Updates:

  • I added a second version of the right side that is slightly looser than the left side, in case you don't want to struggle to slide the rods across. It is 8.32mm instead of 8.18mm.
  • Made the screw holes for the endstop switch a little bigger
  • Added a small shape for test-fitting just the hole
  • Added variations with 44mm and 46mm rod spacing (vs. standard 45mm)

Tired of swapping out spools of filament from my single spool holder, I designed this horizontal spool system for the Taz 6. My present config accommodates four spools.

It's brutally simple and doesn't require much explanation: Use the single-sided holders for each end, and the double-sided holders in the middle. I attach all the holders to my Taz with M5 x 12mm socket head cap screws and M5 t-slot nuts.

The 94mm axle works for all the spools I have on hand, but if you print a lot with narrower spools like Proto-Pasta, there's no reason you can't make shorter axles and accommodate five spools at a time.

Also included is the above-mentioned 94mm axle, as well as a simple tab you can mount and use as a holder to keep filament organized when a particular spool isn't in use.

The double-sided holder does require support for the down-facing axle holder, but the mounting holes actually printed better for me without supports.
